Our research group pre- pared an automatically updated list of amyloid- and probably amyloidogenic molecules, the PDB Amyloid collection, which is freely available at the address http://pitgroup.org/amyloid .
The resulting selection of the PDB entries, called the PDB Amyloid list, is available as an automatically and regularly up- dated list of PDB entries, at the site http://pitgroup.org/amyloid/ .
Prexes The more than 640 PDB entries, available at http://pitgroup.org/ amyloid/ , yield a rich set of amyloid-related molecular structures.
In the present contribution, we consider the prexes of the parallel -sheets of the entries of the PDB Amyloid list http://pitgroup.org/amyloid/ .
Methods First, the dening parallel -sheets, satisfying the conditions (i), (ii) and (iii) in the Introduction, of the PDB Amyloid list http://pitgroup.org/amyloid/ , were identied.

Conclusions By searching for the prexes of the parallel -sheet sections of the entries in the PDB Amyloid list in http://pitgroup.org/amyloid/ , we were able to nd numerous proteins in the whole PDB, from which only very recently were shown that they relate to the amyloid-formation.
The list of the PDB codes of the PDB Amyloid can be viewed and downloaded at http://pitgroup.org/apps/amyloid/amyloid_ list .
